      },
      "output": "The sky appears blue because of a phenomenon called **Rayleigh scattering**.\n\n### How sunlight interacts with the atmosphere\n1. **Sunlight is white light**, which is actually a mixture of many colors (wavelengths) ranging from violet (~400\u202fnm) to red (~700\u202fnm).  \n2. When sunlight enters Earth\u2019s atmosphere, it collides with molecules of nitrogen, oxygen, and other tiny particles.  \n3. These particles are **much smaller than the wavelength of visible light**. In that size regime, scattering follows Rayleigh\u2019s law: the amount of scattered light is **inversely proportional to the fourth power of its wavelength** (\u221d\u202f1/\u03bb\u2074).\n\n### Why blue dominates\n- **Shorter wavelengths scatter more**. Blue light (\u2248450\u202fnm) is scattered roughly 10 times more efficiently than red light (\u2248650\u202fnm).  \n- The scattered blue photons are sent in all directions, including toward our eyes, so the sky looks blue wherever we look away from the Sun.\n\n### Why we don\u2019t see violet even though it scatters even more\n- Human eyes are less sensitive to violet than to blue.  \n- A lot of violet light is absorbed by the upper atmosphere (ozone).  \n- The combination makes blue the dominant color we perceive.\n\n### What happens at sunrise and sunset?\nWhen the Sun is low on the horizon, its light must travel through **much more atmosphere**. The path length increases dramatically, so the short\u2011wavelength blue and violet light get scattered out of the direct line of sight long before the light reaches you. The longer\u2011wavelength reds and oranges survive the journey, giving sunrise and sunset their warm hues.\n\n### Quick summary\n- Sunlight = all colors.  \n- Small atmospheric molecules scatter short wavelengths (blue) far more than long ones (red).  \n- Scattered blue light reaches us from every direction \u2192 sky looks blue.  \n\nThat\u2019s the essence of why our daytime sky is blue!",
